New Records: Aaron Nola earned his 14th victory of the season
The Phillies finished the season with a 95-67 record, their highest since winning 102 games in 2011
Key Match Events: Kyle Schwarber and Weston Wilson each drove in two runs
Luis García Jr. homered in the first inning for Washington
José Ruiz loaded the bases with no outs in the ninth before striking out García and James Wood
Pre-Game Insights: Philadelphia manager Rob Thomson said he was really happy with the way the team finished the season
Washington manager Dave Martinez said nobody wants to go home at this time of year and they want to keep playing
Post-Match Reflections: Nola said it's a goal every year to get to 200-plus innings pitched, but he came within two outs of matching the feat
Martinez said the effort was definitely there this year and their young guys got better and will continue to get better
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Phillies have a bye in the first round of the playoffs and will face either NL Central champion Milwaukee or the NL's third wild card in a division series
The Phillies' victory total was the team's highest since winning 102 games in 2011
Washington's season attendance was 1,967,302, a 5.4% increase over its 2023 total
Others: The Phillies rested regulars Bryce Harper and J.T. Realmuto
Nick Castellanos became the first member of the Phillies to play in 162 games in a season since Freddy Galvis in 2017
